In article <36078l$kh5@cville-srv.wam.umd.edu> rsrodger@wam.umd.edu (R S Rodgers) writes:
>In article <CwM2zs.Aw9@news.hawaii.edu>,
>Dave Tholen <tholen@galileo.ifa.hawaii.edu> wrote:
>>How recently did you see this article?  David Barnes has been reported
>>to have said "8 million", and very recently,
>
>Let's see.  Going by Barnes' other statements and the time delay before
>these have tended to become true (anywhere from 6 months to a year -- I
>understand that IBM researchers have described this delayu in terms of 
>the effect of marketing on what they've labeled "Barnes-Time" or the 
>"Barnes effect" for short), we can guess that OS/2 will sell it's 8millionth
>copy in, oh, mid-December.
>
>Using the term "selling" loosely, of course.  The sales from September
>onward seem more a measure of just how fast IBM can give OS/2 away than how
>fast they could actually _sell_ it.

8 million by Dec. seems like a good guess.

In the case of the OS wars, I think the jury has returned with a
verdict.
If you sell an OS you lose to the guy/gal who gives it away.

MS expects about 10-15% of the installed base to upgrade to WIN95.  (60
million x 15% = 9million)  They predict 30 million users based on total
sales of PC's (apple and etc.) to the public at 40 million.  That means
21 million (or 24 million) coming from agreements, where the WIN95 OS
is basically given away with the computer.

To me the OS/2 give away is an idication that the damn company is
serious about growing the market.
